🔑 DSA Pattern / Concept
Pattern: Greedy + Sorting + Disjoint Set / Slot Allocation

Why?

Each task takes 1 unit of time.

You want to maximize profit while respecting deadlines.

The greedy strategy is:

Sort tasks by profit (descending).

For each task, try to schedule it in the latest available slot ≤ its deadline.

If slot is free, assign it; otherwise skip.

This ensures maximum profit and also maximizes number of tasks.

✅ Algorithm
Sort tasks by profit in descending order.

Maintain an array slots of size N (max deadline).

For each task:

Find the latest free slot ≤ deadline.

If found, schedule task there, add profit, increment count.

Output total profit and number of tasks.

📌 Full C++ Code
cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

struct Task {
    int deadline, profit;
};

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int T; cin >> T;
    while (T--) {
        int N; cin >> N;
        vector<Task> tasks(N);
        for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
            cin >> tasks[i].deadline >> tasks[i].profit;
        }

        // Sort by profit descending
        sort(tasks.begin(), tasks.end(), [](Task &a, Task &b) {
            return a.profit > b.profit;
        });

        int maxDeadline = 0;
        for (auto &t : tasks) maxDeadline = max(maxDeadline, t.deadline);

        vector<int> slot(maxDeadline+1, -1);
        int count = 0, totalProfit = 0;

        for (auto &t : tasks) {
            for (int d = t.deadline; d > 0; d--) {
                if (slot[d] == -1) {
                    slot[d] = t.profit;
                    totalProfit += t.profit;
                    count++;
                    break;
                }
            }
        }

        cout << totalProfit << " " << count << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
